![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

The `--number` option is parsed with `parseInt`, but there's no validation to check if the result is a valid number (e.g., if the user provides a non-numeric string, `parseInt` returns `NaN`). This could lead to unexpected behavior (`slice(0, NaN)` results in an empty array). `commander` allows you to provide a custom parser that can also handle validation.

Example with `commander`:
```typescript
.option('-n, --number <count>', 'Number of commits to show', (value) => {
    const parsedValue = parseInt(value, 10);
    if (isNaN(parsedValue)) {
        throw new commander.InvalidArgumentError('Not a number.');
    }
    return parsedValue;
}, 10)
```
